A HOSPITAL ward assistant who was bust with various types of medicine at her house in Inanda, north of Durban was granted bail of R1 000 on Tuesday.She appeared briefly in the Durban Commercial Crimes Court, where her case was postponed until 18 January for further investigation.The 49-year-old woman works at Mahatma Gandhi Hospital in Phoenix. She was arrested on Friday.The Hawks received a tip-off that she was selling classified medicine cheaply to residents in the area.A resident said: &ldquo;The medication was typically bought by people who don&rsquo;t have the money to travel to clinics or government hospitals. &ldquo;They relied on the woman for the medicine although they clearly knew that what she was doing was against the law.&rdquo;KZN Hawks spokesman Captain Simphiwe Mhlongo said members from the Durban commercial crime unit arrested the woman for possession of suspected stolen property. &ldquo;Members were following up information about a woman selling medicine from her home. &ldquo;Her house is in the Amaoti area of Inanda. &ldquo;Officers swooped on her house and when they searched it, found various types of tablets, small medicine bottles and syringes,&rdquo; said Mhlongo.He said some of the medication was classified as schedule four, which requires a doctor&rsquo;s prescription. &ldquo;She was arrested and charged.&rdquo;